#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:11
msgid ""
"Perform the following operations in the server. In your environment, some "
"dependent packages may be missing. Install them by using: `dnf -y install "
"autoconf automake libtool`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:12
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# wget -c https://github.com/inotify-tools/inotify-tools/archive/refs/tags/3.21.9.6.tar.gz\n"
"[root@Rocky ~]# tar -zvxf 3.21.9.6.tar.gz -C /usr/local/src/\n"
"[root@Rocky ~]# cd /usr/local/src/inotify-tools-3.21.9.6/\n"
"[root@Rocky /usr/local/src/inotify-tools-3.21.9.6]# ./autogen.sh && \\\n"
"./configure --prefix=/usr/local/inotify-tools && \\\n"
"make && \\\n"
"make install\n"
"...\n"
"[root@Rocky ~]# ls /usr/local/inotify-tools/bin/\n"
"inotifywait inotifywatch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:26
msgid ""
"Append the environment variable PATH, write it to the configuration file and "
"let it take effect permanently."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# vim /etc/profile\n"
"...\n"
"PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/inotify-tools/bin/\n"
"[root@Rocky ~]# . /etc/profile\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Why not use the inotify-tools RPM package of the EPEL repository? And the way to use source code to compile and install?**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:37
msgid ""
"The author personally believes that remote data transmission is a matter of "
"efficiency, especially in a production environment, where there are a large "
"number of files to be synchronized and a single file is particularly large. "
"In addition, the new version will have some bug fixes and function "
"expansions, and perhaps the transmission efficiency of the new version will "
"be higher, so I recommend installing inotify-tools by source code. Of "
"course, this is the author's personal suggestion, not every user must follow."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel parameter adjustment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:41
msgid ""
"You can adjust the kernel parameters according to the needs of the "
"production environment. By default, there are three files in **/proc/sys/fs/"
"inotity/**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# cd /proc/sys/fs/inotify/\n"
"[root@Rocky /proc/sys/fs/inotify]# cat max_queued_events ;cat max_user_instances ;cat max_user_watches\n"
"16384\n"
"128\n"
"28014\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:53
msgid "max_queued_events-maximum monitor queue size, default 16384"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:53
msgid ""
"max_user_instances-the maximum number of monitoring instances, the default "
"is 128"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:53
msgid ""
"max_user_watches-the maximum number of files monitored per instance, the "
"default is 8192"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:55
msgid ""
"Write some parameters and values ââto **/etc/sysctl.conf**, examples are as "
"follows. Then use `sysctl -p` to make the files take effect"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (txt)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fs.inotify.max_queued_events = 16384\n"
"fs.inotify.max_user_instances = 1024\n"
"fs.inotify.max_user_watches = 1048576\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "Related commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:67
msgid ""
"The inotify-tools tool has two commands, namely: * **inotifywait**-For "
"continuous monitoring, real-time output results. It is generally used with "
"the rsync incremental backup tool. Because it is a file system monitoring, "
"it can be used with a script. We will introduce the specific script writing "
"later.  * **inotifywatch**-for short-term monitoring, output results after "
"the task is completed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:69
msgid "`inotifywait` mainly has the following options:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (txt)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"-m means continuous monitoring\n"
"-r Recursive monitoring\n"
"-q Simplify output information\n"
"-e specifies the event type of monitoring data, multiple event types are separated by commas in English status\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:78
msgid "The event types are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:96
msgid ""
"| Event Type | Description | |---|---| | access | Access to the contents of "
"a file or directory | | modify | The contents of the file or directory are "
"written | | attrib | The attributes of the file or directory are modified | "
"| close_write | File or directory is opened in writable mode and then closed "
"| | close_nowrite | File or directory is closed after being opened in read-"
"only mode | | close | Regardless of the read/write mode, the file or "
"directory is closed | | open | File or directory is opened | | moved_to | A "
"file or directory is moved to the monitored directory | | moved_from | A "
"file or directory is moved from the monitored directory | | move | There are "
"files or directories that are moved to or removed from the monitoring "
"directory | | move_self | The monitored file or directory has been moved | | "
"create | There are files or directories created in the monitored directory | "
"| delete | A file or directory in the monitored directory is deleted | | "
"delete_self | File or directory and delete | | unmount | File system "
"containing unmounted files or directories |"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:98
msgid "Example: `[root@Rocky ~]# inotifywait -mrq -e create,delete /rsync/`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "Demonstration of `inotifywait` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:102
msgid ""
"Type the command in the first terminal pts/0, and the window is locked after "
"pressing Enter, indicating that it is monitoring"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:103
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# inotifywait -mrq -e create,delete /rsync/\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:109
msgid ""
"In the second terminal pts/1, go to the /rsync/ directory and create a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:110
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# cd /rsync/\n"
"[root@Rocky /rsync]# touch inotify\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:116
msgid "Back to the first terminal pts/0, the output information is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_rsync/06_rsync_inotify.md:117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[root@Rocky ~]# inotifywait -mrq -e create,delete /rsync/\n"
"/rsync/ CREATE inotify\n"
msgstr ""

